post_text:
PUSD's Food Services and Student Support Services are back at it, preparing and delivering meals to students and their families on the Navajo Reservation. Food Services is making and delivering around 1,200 meals per day.
The program was temporarily shut down when the Navajo Nation enacted its Shelter-in-Place order, but the program ramped back up last Monday.
Food Services is delivering to Kaibeto, Inscription House, LeChee, Coppermine and Page, Monday through Friday.
Way to go, Food Services and Student Support Services! You are definitely some of the heroes during this pandemic!

post_text:
Taz Williams, Student Support Services Director posted this earlier about the return of the backpack program. They are bringing back the Backpack Program, but they could use a little help gathering some essential supplies.
If you ever wanted to help the angels, now is your chance.
shared_text:
Tashina Williams
April 14 at 8:14 PM ·

We have been able to continue our backpack program at PUSD. We are trying to provide food boxes for as many other families that are struggling or quarantined as possible. We have been handing out soap, sanitizer and disinfecting wipes as well, especially for our families without running water. We are running low and it is hard to purchase those items on a large scale right now. I am asking for donations of rubbing alcohol, bleach, or hydrogen peroxide if you have any extra to make homemade wipes. Also any plastic containers you may have that we could put them in. I know everyone is struggling right now, but anything you may be able to contribute would be amazing. Please let me know and I will pick it up or arrange a drop off time at the district office. Thank you and please take care.

post_text:
The Lady Sand Devils advance to the state finals after defeating American Leadership Academy tonight. The Sand Devils won 37-35. Torrance Begay, playing with four fouls, got the game's final bucket with 8.7 seconds left on the clock. It was the first time the Sand Devils had led the entire game. On ALA's final possession, Miquedah Taliman tied up the ball leading to a jump ball, and the possession arrow was pointing to Page.
"ALA really wanted this win," said Coach Ryan Whitehorse. "They really disrupted our offense, but we were able to overcome some big obstacles and get the win."
The Lady Sand Devils play in their 4th straight championship game tomorrow night.
Way to go Lady Sand Devils!!!
The below photos are from a game earlier this month.

shared_text:
Page Sand Devil Wrestling
January 26 at 9:20 AM ·

1st ever She Devil Classic is in the books!! Our ladies wrestled really well in the home tournament. We finished runner up as a team to Miyumura who had a really tough team. Sharmayne Crank and Monique Parrish both won the championship in their respective weight classes.
Latasha Slim got runner up to a super tough girl from Miyumura. Aja Curley and Tanisha Zee both also finished 2nd place. Other Page medal winners are also pictured below.
Thank you everyone for all the home support, and to those who helped run the tournament.
The other coaches and wrestlers were very impressed, and flooded us with praise and compliments on your hard work!!
Girls and Boys will both be at home again on Wednesday for the 3A North region tournament. So 1 more chance to come see these ladies wrestle as we get ready for the imortant part of the season (sectionals and state)

The Sand Devils led 29-5 at the end of the first quarter, and the team's second squad saw a lot of action tonight.
Great game tonight!

post_text:
Page teachers Terri Simmons (left), and Denise Boldin (right) were awarded Teachers of the Year by Page VFW Post 9632 Tuesday night. Simmons teaches art at Desert View, and Boldin teaches pre-algebra at Page Middle School. VFW Post Commander James Hall (center) presented the teachers the awards during a ceremony at the Elks Lodge.
Thank you VFW for recognizing two of our excellent teachers, and congratulations Terri and Denise!

post_text: Way to go Wrestling Team!
shared_text:
Page Sand Devil Wrestling
December 7, 2019 at 6:29 PM ·

Panguitch Invitational - Varsity finished 3rd out of 20 teams behind Enterprise and Richfield. Our JV ripped it up and won the whole shootin match! They won 76 matches and had 71 pins all together. Freshman Connor Shirley had the fastest pin for the entire tournament. Coach Penrod and I were extremely impressed with the intensity that our boys had and we were very happy with the commeraderie our team has. They all root each other on and get along well.
106 - Ashton Penrod Freshman 2nd
113 - Zachery Ruiz Jr 1st
120 - Isaac Smith Sr 2nd
138 - Rhyett Whitrock 6th
145 - Hunter Richardson Soph 1st
152 - Kaleb June Sr 1st

post_text:
A big congratulations to the Sand Devils basketball team who are the champions of the Sedona Invitational. They defeated Chino Valley 63-48 in the tournament's opening round, Coconino High School 45-43 Friday night and Lee Williams 58-41 in the championship game Saturday. They are now 6-0 for the season, their best start in several years.
Way to go!
